default1. Summarydefault1.1 Christian relief and development agency Tearfund welcomes this opportunity to contribute to the International Development Select Committee’s inquiry on the 
defaultUK
default’s development work in the Middle East, in particular the crisis in 
defaultSyria
default. In February 2013 Te
defaultarfund launched its own emergency appeal for Syria and thanks to the generosity of its supporters, has raised over £2 million to support partners working through local churches and community organisations in Lebanon, Jordan and Syria to reach those in need
default. Assistance includes pre-school education as well as ongoing trauma care, providing emergency food, funding for accommodation and other everyday essentials for refugees.
default&#xa0;
default1.2 The conflict in Syria has been described as the worst humanitarian disaster sinc
defaulte the end of the cold war
default.The scale of the response is hugely challenging as more than 2.2 million Syrians are hosted in the region, an estimated 84 percent of refugees living outside camps, placing unprecedented strain on communities, infrastructure and 
defaultservices in host countries of Lebanon, Jordan, Turkey, Iraq and Egypt
default. The total registered refugee population in the region is expected to reach 4.1 million by December 2014
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.3 This submission by Tearfund recognises the role that the 
defaultUK
default has played by
default providing one of its largest responses to a humanitarian crisis, and recommends that:
default●
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
